                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="sole" xml:id="hand-1">
                                <p>The text was copied in a <term type="script">slanted ogival
                                        majuscule</term> script, in brown ink, without breathings or
                                    accents.</p>
                                <p>There is decorative use of the double dot, and mute <hi rend="italic">iota</hi> is absent. The ligature ΟΥ is
                                    present.</p>
                                <p>Punctuation used includes the middle point and full stop.</p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <musicNotation>Theta notation is present.</musicNotation>

                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="plainInit">Sections of text begin with enlarged initials
                                in brown ink.</decoNote>

                            <decoNote type="other">The first two lines of the heading marking the
                                beginning of an ode are highlighted with translucent yellow wash
                                    (<locus from="1v" to="1v">verso</locus>) .</decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>

                        <additions>The leaf is marked with the current classmark and the former
                            classmark T.34.</additions>
                    </physDesc>

                    <history>
                        <origin>The manuscript from which this leaf came has been dated to <origDate calendar="gregorian" notAfter="0950" notBefore="0850">between 850
                                and 950</origDate> (Bartolomeo Di Salvo, 'Considerazioni sugli
                            Stichera del vespero e delle laudi del oktoechos bizantino della
                            domenica', <hi rend="italic">Orientalia Christiana Periodica</hi> 33
                            (1967), pp. 159-175 at p. 166; Parpulov, p. 106 n. 26). It has been
                            identified as a product of <origPlace ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/4005365">southern
                                Italy</origPlace> (<bibl>Dieter Harlfinger, 'Beispiele der maiuscola
                                ogivale inclinata vom Sinai aus Damaskus', <hi rend="italic">Ἀληθὴς
                                    φιλία: Studi in onore di Giancarlo Prato</hi>, ed. Marco
                                D'Agostino and Paola Degni (Spoleto 2010), pp. 461-477 at p.
                                465</bibl>).</origin>

                        <provenance>Owned by the <placeName key="place_g1100137" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/1100137">Monastery of St Catherine on Mount Sinai</placeName>. Acquired
                            there by the Biblical scholar <name key="person_v56713311" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/56713311" role="fmo" type="person">
                        <persName type="display">Constantin von
                                    Tischendorf (1815-1874)</persName>
                        <persName type="standard">Tischendorf, Constantin von,
                            1815-1874</persName>
                     </name>.</provenance>

                        <acquisition calendar="gregorian" when="1876">Bought by the University
                            Library from Tischendorf's executors in 1876.</acquisition>
                    </history>

